fields.message: Yes. But in addition to changing the shield, a more visible recognition of the legacy of slavery that is attached to our institution might be more powerful and symbolic. It is important to remove, but we must replace, so as to never forget and to honor those who were victims.
I agree with @Tarsier. Perhaps a monument?
People. We can blame the system, but every system necessarily relies on the people in it (unless you want robots to decide guilt).

I definitely thought there were a lot of flaws with the legal system, but the cops bothered me a lot. The discussion about cops not looking into anyone else and that hurting the defense because they didn't have an alternate story of who did it... what are the checks on cops and their investigations?

Why should a juror recuse himself if he doesn't have any personal conflicts? If he made it through jury selection with these beliefs, that's the problem of the judge, prosecutor, and defense attorney, not the juror.
So you would agree that he should not now be kicked off the jury? Then when would nullification apply?
But in this case, it's not a "personal belief" - it's his interpretation of the constitution, and it's not even an unreasonable interpretation...

I want to say option 3, but, realistically, I would probably encourage my community members to go with option 2. The challenge therein, however, is what's keeping the British from doing the same thing?

Something like this needs to come from a leader or community member who is highly respected. I would struggle to make this decision though, as a leader. How do you balance your integrity with matters of survival.
@Madras why do you think that's true?
Miranda rights say they have a right to a lawyer. We could prevent false testimony by requiring a presence of legal help. No testimony should be admissible that was made without a lawyer present.
but what if they waive the right to legal counsel?
I don't see how the introduction of a pseudonym alters the risk. Learns already craft avatars/personae using the edX username field. It's not like we REALLY know who these learners are currently.
I agree with the decision. The role of the university is to challenge beliefs and foster new modes of understanding.
@rhombus Does the university not also have a responsibility to ensure the safety of students?
@square Can you define what safety means in this context?
Only if it does not interfere with the order of existing threads...

Yes, institutions should foster an environment of learning, where students are encouraged to think critically and exposed to a diverse set of ideas.

On the other hand, supposing I was a vegetarian, I would not like to be compelled to attend a week-long seminar on the best way to eat raw meat! So events need to be organized in a way that is respectful to those with differing points of view.
Yes, for the sake of freedom we should abolish everything, including freedom.

I agree with @Hengyang It does seem a bit reactive to have the new policy be an outright prohibition. Is the issue that once we begin to consider the validity of trigger warnings we struggle to differentiate among what might genuinely warrant one and what might not?
@Mink what about events or, say, texts that are required as part of a course? Should these be optional?
@OP this is a good question. Related to this, how will they find said new thread without using the expandable navigation?
